
https://daler.github.io/blender-for-3d-printing/contents.html

alt is usually used as shift (inverse meaning)

hot keys:
- g: grab. gg: grab and slide along edge
- r: rotate
- s: scale
- numpad .: focuses on object
- o: proportional editing, in mesh edit mode
- f9 for changing mesh settings after clicked somewhere else
- shift d: copy paste stuff
- p: separate into new object in edit mode
- a: select all
- alt click: select particular edge of mesh
- ctrl i: invert selection
- h: hide, alt h: unhide
- f: change brush size in scupting mode
- ctrl drag: inverse effect in scupting mode
- shift + right click: changes 3d cursor (where new objects are dropped) location
- shift + c: places 3d cursor at origin
- shift click: select multiple objects
- ctrl r: loop cut. Can use scroll wheel to change repetitions
- ctrl shift click: preview material shading
- f: forms a face when selected 4 points. Can work with 3, idk
- i: insert a loop cut onto itself. normal loop cut may be enough tho
- shift n: recalculate normals
- alt m: merge verticies together
- e, f: edge loop cut snap mode
- shift e: forms a crease
- m: move to another layer

menus:
- ~: moving around
- z: view modes
- shift a: add
- f3: search features
- n: (optional) properties sidebar
- ctrl p: set parent. Select leaf first, then main object second
- ctrl e: edge stuff
- u: unwrap

middle mouse to orbit, shift middle mouse to pan

modifiers:
- subdivision surface: smoothes out the mesh at render time. Mesh is still the same. If want to permanently do it, then click apply, and then you can move the mesh around, but else, don't need to
- solidify: mesh -> mesh with thickness???
